				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sur=
veying technique</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"=
Surveying">surveying</a> technique. For other uses, see <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-disambig" tit=
le=3D"Levelling (disambiguation)">Levelling (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
"Spirit levelling" redirects here. For the bubble level, see <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spirit_level" title=3D"Spirit level">Spirit leve=
l</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tide_station_leveling.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/1/1a/Tide_station_leveling.jpg/250px-Tide_station_leveling.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"2000" data-file-height=3D"1500"></a><figcaption>A wooden tripod h=
olding an optical level is set up firmly on the ground.</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p><b>Levelling</b> or <b>leveling</b> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/American_English" title=3D"American English">American English</a>; <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_and_British_English_spellin=
g_differences#Doubled_in_British_English" title=3D"American and British Eng=
lish spelling differences">see spelling differences</a>) is a branch of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">survey=
ing</a>, the object of which is to establish or verify or measure the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Height" title=3D"Height">height</a> of =
specified points relative to a datum. It is widely used in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geodesy" title=3D"Geodesy">geodesy</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartography" title=3D"Cartography">cartog=
raphy</a> to measure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertical_posi=
tion" title=3D"Vertical position">vertical position</a> with respect to a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertical_datum" title=3D"Vertical d=
atum">vertical datum</a>, and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onstruction" title=3D"Construction">construction</a> to measure height diff=
erences of construction artifacts. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Photolithography" title=3D"Photolithography">photolithography</a>, the =
same term is used in a lithography machine calibration step measuring or ca=
librating wafer surface height with respect to a reference.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Optical_levelling">Optical =
levelling</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLe=
velling&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Optical l=
evelling"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Baak.svg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
c/ca/Baak.svg/250px-Baak.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"251" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"841" data-file-height=
=3D"843"></a><figcaption>Stadia marks on a crosshair while viewing a metric=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling_rod" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Levelling rod">levelling rod</a> or staff. The top mark is at =
1,500<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>mm and the lower is at 1,345<span =
class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>mm; the distance between those two marks is 1=
55<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>mm, yielding a distance to the rod of=
 15.5<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>m.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Optical levelling</b>, also known as <b>spirit levelling</b> and <b>d=
ifferential levelling</b>, employs an <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Optical_level" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optical level">optical=
 level</a></i>, which consists of a precision telescope with <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crosshair" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Crossh=
air">crosshairs</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stadia_mar=
k" title=3D"Stadia mark">stadia marks</a>. The cross hairs are used to esta=
blish the level point on the target, and the stadia allow range-finding; st=
adia are usually at ratios of 100:1, in which case one metre between the st=
adia marks on the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level_staff" =
title=3D"Level staff">level staff</a></i> (or <i>rod</i>) represents 100<sp=
an class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>metres from the target.
</p><p>The complete unit is normally mounted on a <i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Tripod_(surveying)" title=3D"Tripod (surveying)">tripod<=
/a></i>, and the telescope can freely rotate 360=C2=B0 in a horizontal plan=
e. The surveyor adjusts the instrument's level by coarse adjustment of the =
tripod legs and fine adjustment using three precision levelling screws on t=
he instrument to make the rotational plane horizontal. The surveyor does th=
is with the use of a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bull%27s_e=
ye_level" title=3D"Bull's eye level">bull's eye level</a></i> built into th=
e instrument mount.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Procedure">Procedure</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLevelling&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Procedure"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:NivellementExample.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9=
/97/NivellementExample.svg/250px-NivellementExample.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"213" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"1000" data-file-height=3D"850"></a><figcaption>Diagram showing relation=
ship between two level staff, or rods, shown as 1 and 3. The level line of =
sight is 2.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The surveyor looks through the eyepiece of telescope while an assistant =
holds a vertical level staff which is graduated in inches or centimeters. T=
he level staff is placed vertically using a level, with its foot on the poi=
nt for which the level measurement is required. The telescope is rotated an=
d focused until the level staff is plainly visible in the crosshairs. In th=
e case of a high accuracy manual level, the fine level adjustment is made b=
y an altitude screw, using a high accuracy bubble level fixed to the telesc=
ope. This can be viewed by a mirror whilst adjusting or the ends of the bub=
ble can be displayed within the telescope, which also allows assurance of t=
he accurate level of the telescope whilst the sight is being taken. However=
, in the case of an automatic level, altitude adjustment is done automatica=
lly by a suspended prism due to gravity, as long as the coarse levelling is=
 accurate within certain limits. When level, the staff graduation reading a=
t the crosshairs is recorded, and an identifying mark or marker placed wher=
e the level staff rested on the object or position being surveyed.
</p><p>A typical procedure for a linear track of levels from a known datum =
is as follows. Set up the instrument within 100 metres (110 yards) of a poi=
nt of known or assumed elevation. A rod or staff is held vertical on that p=
oint and the instrument is used manually or automatically to read the rod s=
cale. This gives the height of the instrument above the starting (backsight=
) point and allows the height of the instrument (H.I.) above the datum to b=
e computed.
The rod is then held on an unknown point and a reading is taken in the same=
 manner, allowing the elevation of the new (foresight) point to be computed=
. The difference between these two readings equals the change in elevation,=
 which is why this method is also called <i>differential levelling</i>. The=
 procedure is repeated until the destination point is reached. It is usual =
practice to perform either a complete loop back to the starting point or el=
se close the traverse on a second point whose elevation is already known. T=
he closure check guards against blunders in the operation, and allows resid=
ual error to be distributed in the most likely manner among the stations.
</p><p>Some instruments provide three crosshairs which allow <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stadia_mark" title=3D"Stadia mark">stadia</a> me=
asurement of the foresight and backsight distances. These also allow use of=
 the average of the three readings (3-wire leveling) as a check against blu=
nders and for averaging out the error of interpolation between marks on the=
 rod scale.
</p><p>The two main types of levelling are single-levelling as already desc=
ribed, and double-levelling (double-rodding). In double-levelling, a survey=
or takes two foresights and two backsights and makes sure the difference be=
tween the foresights and the difference between the backsights are equal, t=
hereby reducing the amount of error.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling#cite_note-1"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Double-levelling costs twice as much as single-levelling.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level=
ling#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Turning_a_level">Turning a =
level</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLevell=
ing&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Turning a lev=
el"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>When using an optical level, the endpoint may be out of the effective ra=
nge of the instrument. There may be obstructions or large changes of elevat=
ion between the endpoints. In these situations, extra setups are needed. Tu=
rning is a term used when referring to moving the level to take an elevatio=
n shot from a different location.
</p><p>To "turn" the level, one must first take a reading and record the el=
evation of the point the rod is located on. While the rod is being kept in =
exactly the same location, the level is moved to a new location where the r=
od is still visible. A reading is taken from the new location of the level =
and the height difference is used to find the new elevation of the level gu=
n. This is repeated until the series of measurements is completed.
</p><p>The level must be horizontal to get a valid measurement. Because of =
this, if the horizontal crosshair of the instrument is lower than the base =
of the rod, the surveyor will not be able to sight the rod and get a readin=
g. The rod can usually be raised up to 25 feet high, allowing the level to =
be set much higher than the base of the rod.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Trigonometric_levelling">Tr=
igonometric levelling</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DLevelling&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Trigonometric levelling"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:GPS-m%C3%A4tning_p%C3%A5_j%C3%A4rn%C3%A5lders=
boplats_i_Ytterby_sn,_Bohusl%C3%A4n,_den_28_april_2006._Bild_1.JPG" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/a/a6/GPS-m%C3%A4tning_p%C3%A5_j%C3%A4rn%C3%A5ldersboplats_i_=
Ytterby_sn%2C_Bohusl%C3%A4n%2C_den_28_april_2006._Bild_1.JPG/250px-GPS-m%C3=
%A4tning_p%C3%A5_j%C3%A4rn%C3%A5ldersboplats_i_Ytterby_sn%2C_Bohusl%C3%A4n%=
2C_den_28_april_2006._Bild_1.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2048" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"1536"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archaeo=
logy" title=3D"Archaeology">Archaeological</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">survey</a> using a Leica TPS110=
0 total station on an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_Age" ti=
tle=3D"Iron Age">Iron Age</a> dwelling in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ytterby" title=3D"Ytterby">Ytterby</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Sweden" title=3D"Sweden">Sweden</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The other standard method of levelling in construction and surveying is =
called <b>trigonometric levelling</b>, which is preferred when levelling "o=
ut" to a number of points from one stationary point. This is done by using =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_station" title=3D"Total st=
ation">total station</a>, or any other instrument to read the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenith" title=3D"Zenith">vertical, or zenith an=
gle</a> to the rod, and the change in elevation is calculated using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_functions" title=3D"Trigono=
metric functions">trigonometric functions</a> (see example below). At great=
er distances (typically 1,000 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_s=
urvey_foot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"US survey foot">feet</a> and gre=
ater), the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curvature_of_the_Earth"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Curvature of the Earth">curvature of the Ea=
rth</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Refraction" title=
=3D"Refraction">refraction</a> of the instrument <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Laser" title=3D"Laser">wave</a> through the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Earth" title=3D"Atmosphere of Earth"=
>air</a> must be taken into account in the measurements as well (see sectio=
n below).
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Trigonometrisches_Nivellement.=
jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/Trigonometrisches_Nivellement.jpg/250px-Trigo=
nometrisches_Nivellement.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"18=
0" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"880" data-file-height=3D"63=
4"></a><figcaption>Formulation of trigonometric levelling</figcaption></fig=
ure>
<p>Ex: an instrument at Point A reading to a rod at Point B a zenith angle =
of &lt; 88=C2=B015'22" (degrees, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
inute_of_Arc" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Minute of Arc">minutes, second=
s of arc</a>) and a slope distance of 305.50 feet not factoring rod or inst=
rument height would be calculated thus:
</p>
<dl><dd>cos(88=C2=B015'22")(305.5)=E2=89=88 9.30&nbsp;ft.,</dd></dl>
<p>meaning an elevation change of approximately 9.30 feet in elevation betw=
een Points A and B. So if Point A is at 1,000 feet of elevation, then Point=
 B would be at approximately 1,009.30 feet of elevation, as the reference l=
ine (0=C2=B0) for zenith angles is straight up going clockwise one complete=
 revolution, and so an angle reading of less than 90 degrees (horizontal or=
 flat) would be looking uphill and not down (and opposite for angles greate=
r than 90 degrees), and so would gain elevation.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Refraction_and_curvature">R=
efraction and curvature</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DLevelling&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Refraction and curvature"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling_ref=
raction" title=3D"Levelling refraction">Levelling refraction</a></div>
<p>The curvature of the earth means that a line of sight that is horizontal=
 at the instrument will be higher and higher above a spheroid at greater di=
stances. The effect may be insignificant for some work at distances under 1=
00 meters. The increase in height of a straight line with distance <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span> is:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\sqrt {D^{2}+R^{2}}}-R\approx {\frac {D^{2}}{2R}}\approx 0.0785{\text{ m=
}}(D{\text{ in km}})^{2}\approx 0.0239{\text{ ft}}(D/1000{\text{ ft}})^{2}}=
">
