-align: -0.671ex; width:14.592ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \D=
elta W_{i}=3D\Delta h_{i}g_{i}\ }"></span></dd></dl>
<p>should be used in all computations, producing geopotential values <span =
class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-=
mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D=
"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle W_{i}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>W</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle W_{i}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7301a4cfd04d4f5db4549fdf23746a0d2ce9f387" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.993ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle W_{=
i}}"></span> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benchmark_(su=
rveying)" title=3D"Benchmark (surveying)">benchmarks</a> of the network.
</p><p>High precision levelling, especially when conducted over long distan=
ces as used for the establishment and maintenance of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertical_datum" title=3D"Vertical datum">vertical datums=
</a>, is called <i><b>geodetic levelling</b></i>.<span class=3D"anchor" id=
=3D"Geodetic"></span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-United_States._Department_of_Defen=
se_1973_p._98_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Levelling#cite_note-United_States._Department_of_Defense_1973_p._98-5"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Instruments">Instruments</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLevelling&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Instruments"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling_instrument=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Levelling instrument">Levelling instrument=
</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Classical_instruments">Clas=
sical instruments</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DLevelling&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: C=
lassical instruments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dumpy_level" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Dumpy level">dumpy level</a> was developed by English civi=
l engineer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Gravatt" title=
=3D"William Gravatt">William Gravatt</a>, while surveying the route of a pr=
oposed railway line from London to Dover. More compact and hence both more =
robust and easier to transport, it is commonly believed that dumpy levellin=
g is less accurate than other types of levelling, but such is not the case.=
 Dumpy levelling requires shorter and therefore more numerous sights, but t=
his fault is compensated by the practice of making foresights and backsight=
s equal.
</p><p>Precise level designs were often used for large leveling projects wh=
ere utmost accuracy was required. They differ from other levels in having a=
 very precise spirit level tube and a micrometer adjustment to raise or low=
er the line of sight so that the crosshair can be made to coincide with a l=
ine on the rod scale and no interpolation is required.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Automatic_level">Automatic =
level</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLevell=
ing&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Automatic lev=
el"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Automatic levels make use of a <i>compensator</i> that ensures that the =
line of sight remains horizontal once the operator has roughly leveled the =
instrument (to within maybe 0.05 degree). The compensator consists of small=
 prisms suspended from wires inside of the level's chassis that are connect=
ed together in the shape of a pendulum. This allows for only horizontal lig=
ht rays to enter, even in cases where the telescope of the instrument is no=
t perfectly plumb.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The surveyor sets the instrument up quickly and does not have to re-=
level it carefully each time they sight on a rod on another point. It also =
reduces the effect of minor settling of the tripod to the actual amount of =
motion instead of leveraging the tilt over the sight distance. Because the =
level of the instrument only needs to be adjusted once per setup, the surve=
yor can quickly and easily read as many side-shots as necessary between tur=
ns. Three level screws are used to level the instrument, as opposed to the =
four screws historically found in dumpy levels.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Laser_level">Laser level</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLevelling&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Laser level"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laser_level" title=
=3D"Laser level">Laser level</a></div>
<p>Laser levels<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levelling#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> project a beam wh=
ich is visible and/or detectable by a sensor on the leveling rod. This styl=
e is widely used in construction work but not for more precise control work=
. An advantage is that one person can perform the levelling independently, =
whereas other types require one person at the instrument and one holding th=
e rod.
</p><p>The sensor can be mounted on earth-moving machinery to allow automat=
ed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grading_(engineering)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Grading (engineering)">grading</a>.
</p>
